## Making Rules Generic

When a new fix is discovered (e.g. video controls being wrong, or spacing using wrong units), the rule goes into the knowledge base and this doc as a **generic principle**, not a specific case.

**Pattern:**
- Specific: "Dark hero sections need white button borders" ❌
- Generic: "All spacing tools (set_spacing, set_layout) accept pixels — not Tailwind scale values" ✅ (system-specific: Claude doesn't know our units)

- Specific: "Video controls should be false in hero sections" ❌
- Generic: "Video ambient defaults (autoPlay=true, loop=true, muted=true, controls=false) apply everywhere — only override when the user explicitly requests a media player" ✅ (system-specific: these are OUR component's default props)

- Specific: "Build pricing cards dynamically" ❌
- Generic: "Any repeated structure (cards, rows, list items) → set_repeat + ONE template node; never N static copies" ✅ (system-specific: the set_repeat tool and context.item.data.* binding syntax are not general knowledge — Claude cannot infer that our system supports a repeat mechanism or what the exact call signature is)

- Specific: "Tell Claude to check contrast before finishing a section" ❌
- Correct: nothing — Claude has the live palette hex values and knows how to design ✅

- Specific: "The hero's gap should be 16px" ❌
- Correct: nothing — specific pixel values are design decisions Claude makes ✅

**Rule for adding a new rule:** Ask "is this something Claude cannot know without being told?" If Claude can derive it from general design, CSS, or engineering knowledge — don't add it. Only add system-specific facts: our token names, our tool params, our quirks, our formula syntax.

